 2 -2h7l5 5v11a2 2 0 0 1 -2 2z\"></path><path d=\"M9 9l1 0\"></path><path d=\"M9 13l6 0\"></path><path d=\"M9 17l6 0\"></path></svg><span>Resume</span></a></li><li><a class=\"flex min-h-[48px] items-center gap-3 rounded-xl px-4 py-3 text-base font-medium transition-colors text-[var(--text-secondary)] hover:bg-[var(--surface-secondary)] hover:text-[var(--text-primary)]\" href=\"/contact\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" class=\"h-5 w-5 shrink-0\"><path d=\"M3 7a2 2 0 0 1 2 -2h14a2 2 0 0 1 2 2v10a2 2 0 0 1 -2 2h-14a2 2 0 0 1 -2 -2v-10z\"></path><path d=\"M3 7l9 6l9 -6\"></path></svg><span>Contact</span></a></li></ul></div></div></div></header><div class=\"min-h-screen\"><main id=\"main-content\" role=\"main\" aria-label=\"Portfolio Content\" tabindex=\"-1\"><div class=\"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-10 md:py-14\"><script type=\"application/ld+json\">{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"BreadcrumbList\",\"@id\":\"https://isaacavazquez.com#breadcrumb\",\"itemListElement\":[{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":1,\"name\":\"Home\",\"item\":\"https://isaacavazquez.com/\"},{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":2,\"name\":\"Writing\",\"item\":\"https://isaacavazquez.com/writing\"},{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":3,\"name\":\"Building a Fantasy Football Rankings Platform That Keeps Draft Decisions Honest\",\"item\":\"https://isaacavazquez.com/writing/building-a-fantasy-football-rankings-platform\"}]}</script><script type=\"application/ld+json\">{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"Article\",\"@id\":\"https://isaacavazquez.com/writing/building-a-fantasy-football-rankings-platform#article\",\"headline\":\"Building a Fantasy Football Rankings Platform That Keeps Draft Decisions Honest\",\"description\":\"Learn how I built a fantasy football rankings platform that keeps public rankings, scoring toggles, freshness timestamps, and the draft assistant aligned around the same published snapshot data.\",\"url\":\"https://isaacavazquez.com/writing/building-a-fantasy-football-rankings-platform\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-04-02\",\"dateModified\":\"2026-04-02\",\"inLanguage\":\"en-US\",\"isAccessibleForFree\":true,\"image\":[\"https://isaacavazquez.com/og-image.png\"],\"author\":{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"Person\",\"@id\":\"https://isaacavazquez.com#person\",\"name\":\"Isaac Vazquez\",\"alternateName\":\"Isaac Vazquez\",\"description\":\"Product Manager and UC Berkeley Haas MBA Candidate with 5+ years building SaaS products reaching 60M+ users. Case studies, product thinking, and PM frameworks.\",\"url\":\"https://isaacavazquez.com\",\"image\":\"https://isaacavazquez.com/opengraph-image\",\"sameAs\":[\"https://linkedin.com/in/isaac-vazquez\",\"https://github.com/IsaacAVazquez\"],\"jobTitle\":\"Technical Product Manager & UC Berkeley MBA Candidate\"},\"articleSection\":\"Fantasy Football\",\"wordCount\":1049,\"keywords\":\"fantasy football rankings platform, fantasy draft assistant, fantasy football analytics, snapshot-backed rankings, fantasy football product design, draft strategy tools\"}</script><div class=\"min-h-screen py-16 sm:py-20 px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8\"><article class=\"max-w-4xl mx-auto\"><header class=\"mb-12\"><h1 class=\"text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-100 mb-4\">Building a Fantasy Football Rankings Platform That Keeps Draft Decisions Honest</h1><div class=\"flex items-center gap-4 text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 mb-6\"><time dateTime=\"2026-04-02\">April 1, 2026</time><span>•</span><span>6 min read</span><span>•</span><span>1049<!-- --> words</span></div><div class=\"flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-8\"><span class=\"px-3 py-1 text-sm font-medium bg-neutral-100 dark:bg-neutral-800 text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300 rounded-full\">Fantasy Football</span><span class=\"px-3 py-1 text-sm font-medium bg-neutral-100 dark:bg-neutral-800 text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300 rounded-full\">Fantasy Football Analytics</span><span class=\"px-3 py-1 text-sm font-medium bg-neutral-100 dark:bg-neutral-800 text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300 rounded-full\">Draft Strategy</span><span class=\"px-3 py-1 text-sm font-medium bg-neutral-100 dark:bg-neutral-800 text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300 rounded-full\">Rankings</span><span class=\"px-3 py-1 text-sm font-medium bg-neutral-100 dark:bg-neutral-800 text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300 rounded-full\">Sports Product</span><span class=\"px-3 py-1 text-sm font-medium bg-neutral-100 dark:bg-neutral-800 text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300 rounded-full\">Data Products</span><span class=\"px-3 py-1 text-sm font-medium bg-neutral-100 dark:bg-neutral-800 text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300 rounded-full\">Next.js</span></div></header><div class=\"prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert max-w-none mb-12\"><h1>Building a Fantasy Football Rankings Platform That Keeps Draft Decisions Honest</h1>\n<p>If you want to try the product first, start with the <a href=\"/fantasy-football\">Fantasy Football Rankings board</a> and then open the <a href=\"/fantasy-football/draft-tracker\">Draft Assistant</a>.</p>\n<p>Fantasy football tools often fail in a predictable way: the rankings say one thing, the draft tool says another, and the freshness of the data is hard to verify. That gap creates exactly the kind of confusion a fantasy product is supposed to remove.</p>\n<p>I built this platform around a stricter product idea: rankings first, draft utility second. The public board and the draft assistant should behave like parts of the same system, not neighboring tools that happen to share a logo.</p>\n<h2>The Problem With Most Fantasy Product Workflows</h2>\n<p>In-season and draft-season fantasy decisions are full of false confidence.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Rankings may not clearly state when they were last updated.</li>\n<li>Scoring-format switches can quietly change the underlying list in ways users do not notice.</li>\n<li>Draft tools may apply their own logic that drifts away from the published board.</li>\n<li>Position views can imply precision even when a source does not actually support that slice cleanly.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The end result is a tool that feels active but does not feel trustworthy.</p>\n<p>For fantasy players, that matters. Draft decisions are fast, emotional, and hard to reverse. A product that adds ambiguity at the moment of decision is doing the opposite of its job.</p>\n<h2>Why This Product Is Built Around Published Snapshots</h2>\n<p>The foundation of the product is published snapshot data. That sounds less glamorous than \"real-time AI,\" but it solves the right problem.</p>\n<p>A published snapshot gives the user a stable reference point:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>the season and week are clear</li>\n<li>the last updated timestamp is visible</li>\n<li>the scoring format is explicit</li>\n<li>the same source data can power both the rankings board and the draft assistant</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This improves trust because the product is honest about freshness instead of implying constant live precision it cannot guarantee.</p>\n<p>It also improves interface consistency. When the rankings page and the draft tracker both read from the same published snapshot, users do not have to wonder whether the \"best available\" list was generated from different assumptions than the public board.</p>\n<p>That consistency is the central product decision.</p>\n<h2>The Key Decisions And Tradeoffs</h2>\n<h3>1. Rankings First, Draft Utility Second</h3>\n<p>The hero line on the page says it directly: rankings first, draft utility second.</p>\n<p>That framing matters because it keeps the product anchored to a clear public artifact: the board. The draft assistant exists to make that board usable in a live draft, not to invent a separate decision model behind the scenes.</p>\n<p>This makes the user experience more predictable. If a player is ranked a certain way on the board, the draft tool should reflect that ordering rather than surprise the user with a hidden override.</p>\n<h3>2. Scoring Toggles Need To Change More Than The Label</h3>\n<p>PPR, Half PPR, and Standard formats are not cosmetic switches. They create different player values, different position tradeoffs, and different draft behaviors.</p>\n<p>That is why the platform treats scoring as route state and data state, not just UI state. The toggle changes the published board the user is looking at, and the timestamps stay attached to that specific view.</p>\n<p>This is a small implementation detail with big trust implications. When scoring changes, the user should feel they are looking at a different board, not the same board with a different badge.</p>\n<h3>3. Unsupported Slices Should Be Labeled, Not Faked</h3>\n<p>One of my favorite decisions in the product is also one of the least flashy: unsupported scoring-position combinations are marked as unavailable instead of silently falling back to something adjacent.</p>\n<p>That preserves honesty. A fallback can be useful, but an unlabeled fallback reads like authority. In a fantasy rankings tool, that is dangerous because people draft directly from the screen.</p>\n<p>I would rather show a clear limitation than manufacture confidence.</p>\n<h2>How The Experience Works</h2>\n<p>The platform is built to support two connected behaviors:</p>\n<h3>Research The Board</h3>\n<p>The public rankings route lets users:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>move between overall and position-specific views</li>\n<li>switch across scoring systems</li>\n<li>search the board quickly</li>\n<li>inspect tier groupings and player context</li>\n<li>see freshness metadata for the published snapshot</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This makes the board useful as a reference surface even outside a live draft.</p>\n<h3>Operate Inside A Draft</h3>\n<p>The draft assistant builds on the same published rankings and adds draft-specific utility. That combination matters because a draft room is not just a list-reading exercise. Users need help staying oriented while picks disappear, rosters evolve, and positional runs distort the room.</p>\n<p>The assistant works because it is connected to the same source logic as the board instead of trying to be a separate rankings universe.</p>\n<h2>Why Alignment Matters More Than Feature Volume</h2>\n<p>Many sports products try to win by stacking extra features: projections, news, AI blurbs, matchup overlays, recommendation badges, and endless filters.</p>\n<p>Those can all be useful, but if the underlying ranking logic is inconsistent across surfaces, the product still feels unstable.</p>\n<p>This project leans in the opposite direction. It prioritizes internal alignment:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>one published data source</li>\n<li>one visible freshness model</li>\n<li>one clear scoring context</li>\n<li>one relationship between the board and the draft tool</li>\n</ul>\n<p>That makes the experience easier to trust, and trust is a stronger retention feature than novelty.</p>\n<h2>What This Project Taught Me</h2>\n<p>Fantasy football is a great product-design sandbox because the decisions are frequent, the users are opinionated, and the cost of confusion is immediate.</p>\n<p>The biggest lesson from this project is that utility products become better when they are explicit about their boundaries. A timestamp, an unavailable-state label, and a consistent source model do more for credibility than a dozen extra product flourishes.</p>\n<p>The second lesson is that connected surfaces matter. A rankings board is more valuable when it translates cleanly into draft behavior. A draft tool is more valuable when users know exactly where its recommendations come from.</p>\n<h2>Try The Live Product</h2>\n<p>You can explore the published board at <a href=\"/fantasy-football\">Fantasy Football Rankings</a> and then test the same logic inside the <a href=\"/fantasy-football/draft-tracker\">Draft Assistant</a>.</p>\n<p>The product is easiest to understand if you switch scoring formats, compare overall versus position views, and then move into the draft tracker to see how the same rankings hold together in a faster, higher-pressure workflow.</p>\n</div><div class=\"mt-16 mb-12\"><div class=\"card p-8 \" itemScope=\"\" itemType=\"https://schema.org/Person\" itemProp=\"author\" style=\"opacity:0;transform:translateY(20px)\"><div class=\"flex flex-col sm:flex-row items-start gap-6\"><div class=\"flex-shrink-0\"><img alt=\"Isaac Vazquez\" itemProp=\"image\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"120\" height=\"120\" decoding=\"async\" data-nimg=\"1\" class=\"rounded-lg\" style=\"color:transparent\" srcSet=\"/_next/image?url=%2Fimages%2Fisaac-headshot.jpg&amp;w=128&amp;q=75 1x, /_next/image?url=%2Fimages%2Fisaac-headshot.jpg&amp;w=256&amp;q=75 2x\" src=\"/_next/image?url=%2Fimages%2Fisaac-headshot.jpg&amp;w=256&amp;q=75\"/></div><div class=\"flex-1\"><div class=\"mb-4\"><h3 class=\"text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--text-primary)] mb-2\" itemProp=\"name\">About the Author</h3><h4 class=\"text-xl font-semibold text-[var(--text-primary)] mb-1\">Isaac Vazquez</h4><p class=\"text-base text-[var(--text-tertiary)]\" itemProp=\"jobTitle\">Technical Product Manager &amp; UC Berkeley Haas MBA Candidate</p></div><p class=\"text-base text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed\" itemProp=\"description\">Product manager with 6+ years across SaaS and high-scale consumer platforms, currently pursuing MBA at UC Berkeley Haas. Building mission-driven products that balance user insight, data-driven decisions, and cross-functional collaboration.</p><div class=\"mb-4\"><p class=\"text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--text-primary)] uppercase tracking-wider mb-2\">Credentials &amp; Experience</p><div class=\"grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-2\"><div class=\"flex items-start gap-2\" itemProp=\"hasCredential\" itemScope=\"\" itemType=\"https://schema.org/EducationalOccupationalCredential\"><span class=\"text-[var(--text-primary)]\">•</span><span class=\"text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)]\" itemProp=\"name\">UC Berkeley Haas MBA Candidate &#x27;27</span></div><div class=\"flex items-start gap-2\" itemProp=\"hasCredential\" itemScope=\"\" itemType=\"https://schema.org/EducationalOccupationalCredential\"><span class=\"text-[var(--text-primary)]\">•</span><span class=\"text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)]\" itemProp=\"name\">Consortium Fellow</span></div><div class=\"flex items-start gap-2\" itemProp=\"hasCredential\" itemScope=\"\" itemType=\"https://schema.org/EducationalOccupationalCredential\"><span class=\"text-[var(--text-primary)]\">•</span><span class=\"text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)]\" itemProp=\"name\">MLT Professional Development Fellow</span></div><div class=\"flex items-start gap-2\" itemProp=\"hasCredential\" itemScope=\"\" itemType=\"https://schema.org/EducationalOccupationalCredential\"><span class=\"text-[var(--text-primary)]\">•</span><span class=\"text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)]\" itemProp=\"name\">6+ years in SaaS and consumer technology</span></div></div></div><div class=\"mb-4\"><p class=\"text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--text-primary)] uppercase tracking-wider mb-2\">Areas of Expertise</p><div class=\"flex flex-wrap gap-2\"><span class=\"px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium bg-[var(--surface-secondary)] text-[var(--text-secondary)] rounded-full\" itemProp=\"knowsAbout\">Product Management</span><span class=\"px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium bg-[var(--surface-secondary)] text-[var(--text-secondary)] rounded-full\" itemProp=\"knowsAbout\">Product Strategy</span><span class=\"px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium bg-[var(--surface-secondary)] text-[var(--text-secondary)] rounded-full\" itemProp=\"knowsAbout\">Quality Engineering</span><span class=\"px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium bg-[var(--surface-secondary)] text-[var(--text-secondary)] rounded-full\" itemProp=\"knowsAbout\">Data Analytics</span><span class=\"px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium bg-[var(--surface-secondary)] text-[var(--text-secondary)] rounded-full\" itemProp=\"knowsAbout\">User Research</span><span class=\"px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium bg-[var(--surface-secondary)] text-[var(--text-secondary)] rounded-full\" itemProp=\"knowsAbout\">Cross-functional Leadership</span></div></div><div class=\"flex items-center gap-4 pt-4 border-t border-[var(--border-primary)]\"><p class=\"text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--text-primary)]\">Connect:</p><a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" class=\"flex items-center gap-2 text-[var(--text-tertiary)] hover:text-[var(--text-primary)] transition-colors\" aria-label=\"LinkedIn Profile\" itemProp=\"sameAs\" href=\"https://linkedin.com/in/isaac-vazquez\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" class=\"tabler-icon tabler-icon-brand-linkedin w-5 h-5\"><path d=\"M8 11v5\"></path><path d=\"M8 8v.01\"></path><path d=\"M12 16v-5\"></path><path d=\"M16 16v-3a2 2 0 1 0 -4 0\"></path><path d=\"M3 7a4 4 0 0 1 4 -4h10a4 4 0 0 1 4 4v10a4 4 0 0 1 -4 4h-10a4 4 0 0 1 -4 -4l0 -10\"></path></svg><span class=\"text-sm\">LinkedIn</span></a><a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" class=\"flex items-center gap-2 text-[var(--text-tertiary)] hover:text-[var(--text-primary)] transition-colors\" aria-label=\"GitHub Profile\" itemProp=\"sameAs\" href=\"https://github.com/IsaacAVazquez\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" class=\"tabler-icon tabler-icon-brand-github w-5 h-5\"><path d=\"M9 19c-4.3 1.4 -4.3 -2.5 -6 -3m12 5v-3.5c0 -1 .1 -1.4 -.5 -2c2.8 -.3 5.5 -1.4 5.5 -6a4.6 4.6 0 0 0 -1.3 -3.2a4.2 4.2 0 0 0 -.1 -3.2s-1.1 -.3 -3.5 1.3a12.3 12.3 0 0 0 -6.2 0c-2.4 -1.6 -3.5 -1.3 -3.5 -1.3a4.2 4.2 0 0 0 -.1 3.2a4.6 4.6 0 0 0 -1.3